<font color="#FF0000">TO CLASS LASS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Oct 25 17:11:21 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Nice post Betty. May I call you Betty?<br><br>
First off, I want to say that I appreciate you going to Vietnam to help the guys. <br><br>
Help the guys. Sounds simple doesn't it? Simple yet noble.<br><br>
We have a tendency, as humans, to want our labor to be recognized. A pat on the back usually suffices. Unfortunately when you and I returned from RVN we didn't always get that recognition.<br><br>
I think we are at a place in time where many of us are in the venting stage. Much anger. Some of us are still hiding behind the paddy dike that Cook has often (and accurately) alluded to. The venting indicates this to me - that some are still pinned down behind the dike.<br><br>
I know, firsthand, what it is like to get up from behind a real paddy dike (a small bomb crater actually) and face the enemy when I didn't know whether or not he was dead. Quite scary. I am still numb about much that happened in Vietnam.<br><br>
In many ways our fellow soldiers (I say &quot;our&quot; because I consider you one of us) are just as fearful of stepping out into the open today. I can't go into all of the reasons here and now. But, I will say that what Cook says is very real, considering the stereotypical way Vietnam Vets are viewed.<br><br>
Reactions on this site to what *you* say, quite possibly, are defense mechanisms (strange how I am learning all the lingo). We often hurt the ones we love.<br><br>
Hang in there, Betty. Keep posting. And keep a stiff upper lip.<br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net.  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


